Of the many charges brought against Bacon, as a philosopher y and a reformer of science, there are three, connected with the present subject, which it would be vain to deny, though, in the course oi this enquiry, we may find something to plead in extenuation os them. The first is that he was a Dilettante in science. The second, that he was imperfectly acquainted with the existing state of knowledge. The third, that he grossly exaggerated the defects oi his own time,
